IO redirection:
standard output redirect: 
$ echo $SHELL > shell.txt
$ cat shell.txt
/bin/bash

$ echo "This is blabla" >> shell.txt                 // >> append the contents at the end of the file rather than overwrite the contents (if use >)
$ cat shell.txt
/bin/bash
This is blabla

standard error redirect:
$ cat file 2> error.txt                      // 2> sends standard error output string to the file, 2 is file descriptor of standard error output stream, 1 is file descriptor of standard output
$ cat error.txt
error msg blabla here in red

$ cat file 2>> shell.txt                     // 2>> appends rather than overwrite
$ cat shell.txt
/bin/bash
This is blabla
error msg blabla here in red

$ cat file 2> /dev/null                      //  /dev/null is null device where you send standard output or standard error when you dont need to store or print them


command line pipes: grep
$ cat sample.txt
hello there!
Nice to see you here!

$ grep Hello sample.txt > file.txt
$ less file.txt                              //nothing to output, because there's no Hello, there's only hello (lowercase h); less is output in pager

$ grep hello sample.txt | less               //the output of "grep hello sample.txt" becomes the standard input of "less" command
hello there!
(END)

$ less sample.txt
hello there!
Nice to see you here!
sample.txt (END)

command line pipes: tee (redirect)
$ echo $SHELL | tee shell.txt               //redirect output to file shell.txt
/bin/bash

$ cat shell.txt
/bin/bash

$ echo "blabla" | tee -a shell.txt          //tee -a append rather than overwrite
blabla

$ cat shell.txt
/bin/bash
blabla
















